<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jets Brace for Jaguars Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J (AP) -- The Jacksonville Jaguars aren't  
looking at the New York Jets as just another opponent. They're 
approaching Monday night's game as an opportunity to slap down a 
championship contender. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, the Jets are 1-3 and racked with injuries. Never mind,  
according to the Jaguars (3-1), who still believe the road to their 
first Super Bowl could go through the Meadowlands. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you win, it puts those guys farther from making the  
playoffs,'' Jacksonville receiver Keenan McCardell said. ``That's a 
team capable of getting on a run. Knock them out early and you 
won't have to deal with them later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets were reeling, ready for a knockout, before winning  
their first game last weekend at Denver. Coincidentally, it was the 
Broncos who knocked them out of the playoffs in last season's AFC 
title game, and it was the Jets who knocked the Jags out of the 
playoffs the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, New York believes it has some life. Beating Jacksonville  
would reinforce those feelings and keep the Jets looking up and 
feeling up. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just like a loss causes you to second-guess,'' linebacker  
Bryan Cox said, ``a win causes you to exude confidence. You can put 
yourself on a roll, that's what winning does, it adds a certain 
amount of confidence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams' confidence should come from the performances of  
their defenses. Although their offenses were touted coming into the 
season, New York's has sputtered greatly due to injuries, while 
Jacksonville's has been inconsistent since an opening rout of San 
Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The defenses have turned around some games, most notably last  
week in the Jets' victory at Denver, when they forced six 
turnovers, and in the Jaguars' win at Pittsburgh, when they held 
the Steelers to 216 yards of offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacksonville is far more aggressive on defense under new  
coordinator Dom Capers, the former Carolina head coach who came to 
prominence while overseeing Pittsburgh's superb defenses earlier in 
the decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not totally different, but we do have different people  
who are performing and performing well,'' coach Tom Coughlin said. 
``We don't have as many health issues. Guys are on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got guys like Carnell Lake, Gary Walker, Fernando  
Bryant, Tony Brackens being able to stay healthy. Lonnie Marts is 
making his contribution. It's a matter of different people, playing 
with confidence, and guys who are meeting the physical challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It will present a strong challenge to the Jets, who might have  
star receiver Wayne Chrebet back from a broken foot. That would 
make quarterback Rick Mirer's job a lot easier. 
</P>
<P>
	Mirer hasn't hurt the Jets the last two weeks, but he hasn't  
been sensational, either. New York will settle for solid from the 
man who has replaced Vinny Testaverde (torn Achilles' tendon). 
</P>
<P>
	And Jacksonville would settle for the same from its struggling  
attack, from quarterback Mark Brunell to the running backs, 
receivers and line. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason we've struggled is the little things,'' Brunell  
said. ``I don't know if it's pressing too much or not enough. We've 
got to get it going. Everyone realizes that. No one is more 
disappointed in it than we are as players, because we think we've 
got a pretty good offense. We'll get it going. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of times in my career, we've been in a slump.  
Fortunately, all those times, we've come out of it. We've grown and 
we've learned. This is no different. We've got some improving to do 
and we'll do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If they do it Monday night, one potential playoff thorn might be  
as good as removed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
