<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Oct. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	UFCW Labor Union Backs Gore  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The board of the United Food and Commercial  
Workers voted unanimously today to put its 1.4 million members 
behind Vice President Al Gore in his bid for the Democratic 
presidential nomination. The endorsement came at the urging of John 
Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO labor federation, who met 
privately with the UFCW board today to press Gore's case. UFCW 
President Doug Dority spoke with both Gore and Democratic rival 
Bill Bradley over the weekend. Presidents of the AFL-CIO's biggest 
unions, including the UFCW, will vote to recommend the federation's 
overall endorsement, which in turn will be decided by all 68 member 
unions. 

</P>
<P>
	Mexico Flooding Death Toll at 333  
</P>
<P>
	VILLAHERMOSA, Mexico (AP) -- Angry over sandbagging that has  
swamped their neighborhoods and furious that the government hasn't 
done more to help, hundreds of people in Tabasco's flooded capital 
clashed today with police. Many were beaten and arrested. The death 
toll, according to officials in the affected states, stands at 333. 
But hundreds more were missing, and unofficial counts by local 
newspapers -- based in part on witness accounts -- put the death toll 
as high as 600. President Ernesto Zedillo has called the flooding 
Mexico's worst disaster in a decade. 

</P>
<P>
	Israel To Open Gaza Route Next Week  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- A safe passage route for Palestinian travel  
between Gaza and the West Bank was expected to open in a week, 
Palestinian and Israeli officials said Sunday. The 27-mile passage, 
allowing thousands of Palestinians to visit each other, would be 
the most substantive result of the peace process revived last month 
by Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser 
Arafat. 

</P>
