<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Party Factions Spar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reform Party leaders kept up their sniping at  
one another Sunday, using Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura and 
presidential hopeful Pat Buchanan as targets in a factional fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura, the party's highest-elected official, raised no  
objections to developer Donald Trump's potential candidacy for the 
party's presidential nomination. But Ventura questioned whether he 
could back Buchanan, who is considering leaving the GOP 
presidential race to seek the Reform Party nod. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the outgoing Reform Party chairman, Russell Verney, said  
Ross Perot, the party's presidential nominee in 1992 and 1996, has 
not ruled out a third run. 
</P>
<P>
	The loudest voices behind the internal bickering belonged to  
Verney and his successor, Jack Gargan, a Ventura ally who takes 
over Jan. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Verney again pressed for Ventura to quit the party, citing  
comments the former wrestler made in a recent interview in Playboy 
magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, Ventura said organized religion is for  
``weak-minded people'' and that the Navy's Tailhook sexual 
harassment scandal was ``much ado about nothing.'' Ventura later 
said his remarks about religion referred to extremists and has said 
repeatedly since that he doesn't condone the actions at Tailhook. 
</P>
<P>
	Verney, speaking Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' said  
Ventura's statements were ``an affront to the values of the members 
of the Reform Party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Gargan wondered why Verney was not condemning Buchanan with  
the same vengeance. A new book by the political commentator argues 
that Adolf Hitler was not a direct threat to the United States 
after 1940, a year before the United States entered World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	``How come we don't hear this righteous indignation that he  
(Buchanan) should be thrown out,'' Gargan asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``First, he's not a member of this party,'' Verney responded.  
``And second, if he's a member of this party and he's embodied as 
the leadership of this party in the public's mind, he will be held 
-- everyone will be held to the same standard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both Gargan and Ventura questioned whether the organization  
should nominate Buchanan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very different on social issues,'' Ventura said on ABC's  
``This Week.'' ``Mr. Buchanan likes to put social issues to the 
forefront. We in the Reform Party traditionally have never done 
that, and I agree with that. I don't like putting social issues out 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Buchanan and Trump talk about seeking the Reform  
nomination, Verney said party founder Perot has not ruled out 
another presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ross Perot is one of the most effective communicators in  
America,'' Verney said on CNN's ``Late Edition.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
