<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 13:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Details About Post-Traumatic Stress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Post-traumatic stress disorder can occur as an acute disorder  
soon after the trauma,or have a delayed onset in which the symptoms 
occur more than 6 months after the trauma. 
</P>
<P>
	It can occur at any age and can follow a natural disaster such  
as flood or fire, a man-made disaster such as war or imprisonment, 
or violence such as assault or rape. Such events produce stress in 
anyone, but not everyone will develop the syndrome. The cause is 
not known, but psychological, genetic, physical, and social factors 
may contribute. 
</P>
<P>
	To be diagnosed with post-traumatic stress disorder, the  
American Psychiatric Association says symptoms from each of these 
groups must severely interfere with your life for at least a month: 
</P>
<P>
	--Intrusion: The traumatic event suddenly ``intrudes'' into your  
life, often in vivid flashbacks or nightmares. You may have 
inexplicable sudden onslaughts of emotion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Avoidance: You may feel numb and avoid close ties with others  
as well as situations that remind you of the trauma. Depression, 
``survivor's guilt,'' shame and feelings of failure and 
unworthiness are common. 
</P>
<P>
	--Hyperarousal or hyperalertness: You may begin to act as if you  
were constantly threatened, becoming irritable, ``on guard'' or 
explosive for no reason. Difficulty concentrating or remembering, 
exaggerated ``startle reactions,'' insomnia and panic attacks are 
common. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991010.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 20:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WNBA Seeks Funds During NBA Lockout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Seattle's WNBA expansion team has sold the 5,500  
season tickets it needed to secure a franchise, but coach Linn Dunn 
isn't celebrating. 
</P>
<P>
	The reason: The Seattle City Council is asking for more money  
for the team's three-year lease agreement at KeyArena, and team 
officials say they can't afford it. 
</P>
<P>
	Council president Sue Donaldson has drafted the proposal asking  
for an additional $50,000 a year from the team, which is scheduled 
to begin play next season. If the city council passes it Monday, 
Dunn says Seattle may not have a team after all. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who is Sue Donaldson?'' Dunn asked. ``I don't understand why  
she is doing this. Does she really want to be responsible for 
killing the WNBA's chance to come to Seattle? We won't have a team 
if this happens, I can tell you that right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The WNBA team -- which has no players, name or mascot yet -- faced  
an Oct. 15 deadline to sell 5,500 season tickets and get a 
contracted arena for games. 
</P>
<P>
	With high-profile support from fans like Gov. Gary Locke -- who  
announced last Wednesday that he and his wife were sending in their 
$50 deposits for two season tickets -- the team garnered about 5,900 
ticket pledges by Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	But it might not matter.  
</P>
<P>
	While team officials thought they had a deal with the city,  
Donaldson said there is no agreement signed yet. The original 
proposal sought only expenses, such as ushers, from the team, she 
said, and the additional $50,000 per year is for actual rent. 
</P>
<P>
	Donaldson said the city is cautious after losing revenues from  
KeyArena during the NBA lockout at the start of the 1998-99 season. 
The city estimated it lost $3 million in revenue because of games 
not played by the Seattle SuperSonics. The council sought $341,144 
from the team, but the Sonics won in arbitration and paid only 
$34,000 for the 16 games that weren't played at the arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``We learned from dealing with the Ackerley Group and the NBA  
that we want to make the contract very clear,'' Donaldson said. 
``We don't feel the city should be manipulated again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Council member Peter Steinbrueck said the city is just trying to  
make sure it doesn't get burned if games get canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shouldn't get stuck with these bills,'' Steinbrueck said.  
``There is a desire on the council to make a tighter contract with 
the WNBA because of the NBA. We all want the WNBA here, but it 
needs to be fair and equitable for both parties involved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Team officials complained about the last-minute nature of the  
proposal -- five days before Friday's deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a deal, and we moved forward on that deal,'' said Karen  
Bryant, the team's senior director of operations, who says the city 
and the team came to an agreement in June. ``To change it in the 
11th hour. ... Sue Donaldson owes an explanation to this 
community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Operating under Full House Sports &AMP; Entertainment, the business  
arm of both Seattle's WNBA and Sonics teams, a budget was set to 
bring the team to Seattle. Full House set ticket prices based on 
the team's budget, so adding another $50,000 per year in rent would 
sink the team, Bryant said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to happen,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Sonics pay $874,000 to use the arena. The WNBA team is  
paying considerably less than the $700,000 the city charges 
concerts, ice shows and other events -- an agreement to help the 
team get started. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
