<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coach: Warrick's Heisman Hopes Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida State coach Bobby Bowden feels  
that Peter Warrick's Heisman Trophy hopes are over. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's probably blown,'' Bowden said Sunday after Warrick's  
legal troubles forced him to miss the Seminoles victory over Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	If Warrick returns to the Seminole lineup this season, Bowden  
said he shouldn't worry about any honors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would tell him to take a very back seat, a very back seat,''  
Bowden said when asked his advice for Warrick. ``You go out there 
and play the best you can play and don't even think about the 
Heisman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick and Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton had been among  
the leaders in the chase for the Heisman, college football's most 
coveted individual award. 
</P>
<P>
	But Warrick's chances may have disappeared with his arrest last  
week on a grand theft charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick, teammate Laveranues Coles and a Dillard's department  
store clerk were charged Thursday after the clerk allegedly sold 
them $412.38 worth of clothing for $21.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles, who already was on probation for other violations of team  
rules, was kicked off the team and Warrick was suspended until his 
legal status is determined. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick was scheduled for an initial court appearance Monday,  
but his attorney, John Kenny, said he has filed a written notice of 
appearance, and neither he nor his client would be in court. 
Normally, a trial would be set at least six weeks later. 
</P>
<P>
	Warrick apologized for his actions Saturday and then watched his  
teammates defeat Miami, 31-21. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no way we should make a hero out of this thing,''  
Bowden said. Warrick ``needs to sweat a little bit. But again I 
hope he comes back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden expects to hear little from Warrick about his criminal  
case but advised him, ``Don't hide from it. It's there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And Bowden said Warrick can make the most of a second chance --  
if he gets one. 
</P>
<P>
	``You go out there and just play the best you can and try to get  
the most out of this year you can get,'' Bowden said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
