<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cowboys' Irvin Injured, Leaves Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Dallas Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin was  
taken off the field on a stretcher Sunday after getting hit on the 
head in the first quarter against Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin caught a short pass from Troy Aikman, tried to shake a  
tackle from Bobby Taylor and was hit on the head by safety Tim 
Hauck as he hit the ground. As Taylor tackled Irvin, Hauck's 
shoulder pad collided with the side of Irvin's helmet, twisting his 
head awkwardly as it hit the artificial turf. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys said Irvin sustained trauma to the head and neck and  
had movement in his extremities. He was taken by ambulance to the 
spinal unit of a hospital. Team owner Jerry Jones accompanied Irvin 
in the ambulance. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin moved his fingers and appeared to be talking as he lay on  
his back for more than 10 minutes. He was fitted with a neck brace 
and loaded onto a stretcher as his teammates circled in prayer 
across the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Incredibly, the fans at Veterans Stadium cheered when they first  
realized Irvin was down. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Cowboys' prayer group broke up, Deion Sanders  
nervously circled his fallen teammate while medical staff attended 
to him. Emmitt Smith and Erik Williams stood closest to Irvin. 
After several minutes, Jones came down on the field and walked 
toward the ambulance as Irvin was loaded into the back and driven 
away. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
