<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady: End Trafficking of Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) -- First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton  
issued a call to end the international trade in prostitution on 
Sunday during her last stop in a weeklong European tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at a conference on women and democracy in Iceland's  
capital, she decried a system that allows girls to be lured from 
home with the promise of jobs, ``trafficked like drugs across state 
lines and sold into prostitution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are working to stop trafficking of women and girls in this  
region and around the world,'' she said. ``No government and no 
citizen can rest until we stop this modern form of slavery, protect 
its victims and prosecute those who are responsible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The speech was her most outspoken of the tour, which also took  
her to Italy, Slovakia and Poland. Although she is a likely 
candidate for a U.S. Senate seat from New York in next year's 
elections, Mrs. Clinton has generally avoided directly commenting 
on U.S. political issues during the trip. The White House says the 
trip is not linked to domestic politics. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of her address, more than 300 delegates gave Mrs.  
Clinton a standing ovation. They included representatives from the 
United States, Russia, the Nordic countries, Latvia, Lithuania and 
Estonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Since arriving in Iceland on Friday night, Mrs. Clinton has met  
with President Olafur Ragnar Grimsson and visited the U.S.-Iceland 
Defense Force at its Keflavik Base. About 2,500 U.S. troops are 
stationed at the NATO base under the terms of a 1951 defense 
agreement between the two nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Poor weather prevented her from visiting the Westman Islands on  
Saturday, so Prime Minister David Oddson instead took her on a tour 
of downtown Reykjavik. Later, she saw the ``Islendigur,'' the ship 
that will sail to North America next year to commemorate explorer 
Leif Ericsson's voyage to the continent in the year 1000. 
</P>
<P>
	She also toured the country's Thingvellir National Park and was  
presented with two Icelandic horses, which are to be given to an 
American school. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
