<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 23:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan May Jump to Reform Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- If presidential hopeful Pat Buchanan  
jumps to the Reform Party, he is likely to bring with him a legion 
of supporters who could substantially change the face of the party, 
political analysts say. 
</P>
<P>
	The question for Reformers is whether that influx will make them  
more competitive with the two established parties or make them 
look, as one observer suggests, like ``cranks and malcontents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan is widely expected to announce by month's end that he  
is bolting the Republican Party to seek the Reform presidential 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Some say the commentator would energize the party, bring in new  
members and create a lively contest. Others say his strongly 
conservative views on social issues would turn off voters and make 
it difficult to recruit candidates even as his supporters seize 
control of the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven Schier, a political science professor at Carleton College  
in Northfield, Minn., said Buchanan and his followers would bring 
organization to a party with roots in Texas billionaire Ross 
Perot's 1992 presidential bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan also might get the 5 percent of the vote necessary for  
the party to keep its federal campaign funds, which total $12.6 
million for the 2000 presidential race. 
</P>
<P>
	But Schier argued that Buchanan also would narrow the party's  
appeal and make it ``look like a refuge for cranks and 
malcontents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan and his staff declined to comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota's Reform governor, Jesse Ventura, would prefer another  
candidate, possibly former Connecticut Gov. Lowell Weicker or New 
York developer Donald Trump. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump is forming a committee to explore a run and had a dinner  
meeting with Ventura. Weicker balked at seeking a spot on the 
ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	Dean Barkley, a former Reform Senate candidate who advised  
Ventura in the 1998 campaign, was of two minds about a Buchanan 
candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no doubt this is going to bring more attention and  
energy to our presidential contest than I could dream of, 
especially if it gets into an honest contest between two players,'' 
said Barkley, a member of Ventura's Cabinet as director of the 
state planning agency. 
</P>
<P>
	But if Buchanan joins the party and doesn't play down his  
conservative social views, ``it becomes very problematic,'' Barkley 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reform Party, although sharing many of Buchanan's economic  
stands, has been largely libertarian on abortion, gay rights and 
other social issues that have animated him in three presidential 
campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, Ventura referred Sunday to those stands in questioning  
whether he could support Buchanan's candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very different on social issues,'' Ventura said on ABC's  
``This Week.'' ``Mr. Buchanan likes to put social issues to the 
forefront. We in the Reform Party traditionally have never done 
that, and I agree with that. I don't like putting social issues out 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his new book, Buchanan raises questions about the U.S. entry  
into the war against Nazi Germany, saying the Third Reich was no 
threat to the United States after 1940. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Research Center for the People  
and the Press, said Buchanan's candidacy probably would not improve 
the image of the Reform Party. 
</P>
<P>
	In a Pew poll before the book's release, 7 percent said there  
was a good chance they would vote for Buchanan. Twenty-five percent 
said there was some chance and 63 percent said there was no way 
they would vote for Buchanan. 
</P>
<P>
	Pat Choate, who was Perot's vice presidential running mate, is  
urging Buchanan to join the Reformers, saying he would draw 
millions of voters by focusing on the economy and foreign policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Buchanan above and beyond that is feisty, he's a fantastic  
debater and in the minds of the American public he will give the 
Reform Party equal status with the Democrats and Republicans,'' 
Choate said. 
</P>
<P>
	Party chairman Russell Verney, who is close to Perot, said that  
even if Buchanan brings supporters, he won't overwhelm the party. 
</P>
<P>
	``It isn't as though somebody, and I don't care if they have the  
4th Armored Division with them, can come in and take over the 
party,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	There already are signs that some are unhappy with Buchanan. The  
New Hampshire Reform Party canceled a meeting because of an 
expected flood of Buchanan supporters seeking to become delegates. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyone who requests a ballot can vote in the party's primary. It  
would take a two-thirds vote of national convention delegates to 
set aside the ballot decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Incoming party chairman Jack Gargan is concerned that if  
Buchanan gets enough delegates to next summer's convention in Long 
Beach, Calif., he will be able to overturn a nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he will be a strong candidate, but I certainly want to  
see three or four others,'' Gargan said. He also wants to change 
the convention rules when he takes office in January. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
