<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Local Votes Boost Social Democrats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's Social Democrats  
recovered from a string of losses and held their own in local 
elections in Berlin on Sunday, according to television exit polls. 
</P>
<P>
	The conservative Christian Democrats, led by Berlin mayor  
Eberhard Diepgen, posted gains in the German capital and remained 
the dominant party in local government, the exit polls showed. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Social Democrats held on to second place with 23  
percent, virtually unchanged from the last Berlin election four 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The results of the last major electoral test this year were  
shaping up as a relief for Schroeder, whose popularity has slid 
since he introduced an austerity budget that would cut cherished 
social programs. 
</P>
<P>
	He has insisted that the changes -- including cuts in jobless and  
welfare benefits -- are needed to bring down the national debt and 
secure Germany's economic health. 
</P>
<P>
	The former East German communists, apparently picking up leftist  
voters upset by the Social Democrats' move toward the political 
center, won 17.5 percent, a gain of about three percentage points, 
the exit polls showed. 
</P>
<P>
	The environmentalist Greens, Schroeder's junior partner in the  
year-old federal coalition, were at 10.5 percent, down from 13 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder had declared Berlin, with its 2.4 million eligible  
voters, a national test. At his party's final campaign rally Friday 
night, he said a strong result for the Social Democrats was 
``important not just for this city, but important for the entire 
country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The results indicated that Diepgen, lacking an outright  
majority, would continue his 8-year-old coalition with the Social 
Democrats as junior partner. 
</P>
<P>
	Significantly for Schroeder, that would keep Berlin's four seats  
in the 69-seat upper house of parliament from shifting to the 
conservative opposition, avoiding fresh legislative obstacles for 
the government's plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Social Democrats lost in four state elections  
and in local balloting in North Rhine-Westphalia, which includes 
the Ruhr valley industrial heartland, one of the party's oldest 
strongholds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
