<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Planes Prepare for Antarctic Rescue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) -- Two U.S. Hercules LC-130 cargo  
planes, equipped for a perilous landing at the Antarctic, arrived 
in New Zealand on Sunday to prepare to rescue a polar research 
station's American doctor with a lump in her breast. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Air National Guard planes arrived in Christchurch,  
the gateway to the Antarctic for nations carrying out research 
projects on the polar ice. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Jerri Nielsen is the only physician for a crew of 41  
researchers at the Amundsen-Scott South Pole Station. She has been 
treating herself with chemotherapy since mid-July, when drugs and 
medical equipment were air-dropped during a howling snowstorm. 
</P>
<P>
	The two Hercules planes, manned by three crews, will remain in  
Christchurch until Tuesday before flying south to the McMurdo 
station on the Antarctic coast, where they will wait for the 
temperature to rise above minus 58 degrees before one of them 
attempts the risky 1,600-mile round trip to rescue Nielsen. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures are already rising and the wait is not expected to  
be long. Polar darkness and extreme cold means people do not leave 
the South Pole from February through October. 
</P>
<P>
	A replacement doctor for the station and a team of medics to  
treat Nielsen are on one of the planes, which have skis to allow 
them to land on the ice at Amundsen-Scott base. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane that flies there won't stay any longer than absolutely  
necessary in the fast-changing and hostile Antarctic weather. 
</P>
<P>
	``They will have a half-hour on the ground -- if that -- then  
they'll be out of there,'' said Arthur Brown, a spokesman for the 
National Science Foundation, which runs the base. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers at the South Pole are studying climate changes,  
astronomy and ozone hole depletion. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-day trip to New Zealand started last Wednesday in New  
York. The planes hopped from one U.S. air base to another, 
refueling along the way. Two planes made the trip in case one 
suffers mechanical problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The LC-130s' crews are New York Air National Guard members who  
specialize in flying and landing in Antarctica, making about 270 
missions each season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991010.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 13:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trophy Last Thing on Hamilton's Mind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The Heisman Trophy was the last thing on Joe  
Hamilton's mind. 
</P>
<P>
	The Georgia Tech senior quarterback was struggling through his  
worst game of the season, committing four turnovers. But then he 
led a last-minute drive to tie the game and scored on a 6-yard run 
in overtime to beat North Carolina 31-24 on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Heisman?  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not concerned with it. That's a postseason award. All  
we're doing now is looking forward to winning the rest of the 
season,'' Hamilton said. ``I had a tough game, but that's why it's 
a team game. I don't win by myself and I don't lose by myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton, who has guided the Yellow Jackets high-powered offense  
that averages 41 points and 515.8 yards per game, made it happen 
when it counted. 
</P>
<P>
	Tech moved to 4-1 overall, 2-1 in the Atlantic Coast Conference.  
However, the Yellow Jackets fell one spot to No. 8 with the narrow 
victory over the Tar Heels (1-4, 0-4 ACC). 
</P>
<P>
	With 1:10 left and the Yellow Jackets trailing 24-21 in  
regulation, Tech took over on its own 2-yard line and no time outs 
remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton completed 3-of-4 passes for 73 yards, including two of  
32 and 35 yards to Kelly Campbell, and ran six yards to the Tar 
Heels 19 with eight seconds left in regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Freshman Luke Manget, who had missed two earlier field goals of  
40 yards and 39 yards, came on and hit a 36-yarder to tie it with 
five seconds left. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I caught it a little high. I was loooking up and  
praying that it wasn't going to get blocked,'' said Manget. 
</P>
<P>
	In overtime, Tech took over on the Tar Heels 25 and kept it on  
the ground. Phillip Rogers ran twice for 11 yards and Hamilton 
twice for 14, the last a six-yard quarterback draw for the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Tech's defense took over, stopping the Tar Heels on four  
plays for the win. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton completed 14-of-26 pass attempts for 273 yards and two  
touchdowns, but had two interceptions. He also ran for 77 yards on 
14 carries, but had two fumbles. 
</P>
<P>
	For the season, Hamilton has completed 79 of 117 passing  
attempts for 1,347 yards and 12 TDs with four interceptions. He's 
rushed 68 times for 321 yards and another six scores. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Hamilton's game was his worst of the year, it went much  
better than his counterpart. The Tar Heels lost starting 
quarterback Ronald Curry for the season in the second quarter with 
a torn Achilles. 
</P>
<P>
	Curry scored on a 30-yard scamper before he was injured.  
</P>
<P>
	Tech, held scoreless for the first time all season in the  
opening quarter, fell behind 13-0 before Hamilton connected on the 
47-yard scoring bomb with Campbell 49 seconds before halftime. 
</P>
<P>
	The duo gave the Yellow Jackets their first lead on their first  
possession of the second half on a 59-yard TD strike. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991010.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 19:10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Injury Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dallas receiver Michael Irvin injured his neck and spinal cord  
in Philadelphia on Sunday and was carried off the field in a 
stretcher, but he was able to move his hands and feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin was taken to a hospital, where tests showed swelling in  
the spinal cord and a herniated disc. 
</P>
<P>
	Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, who rode in the ambulance with Irvin,  
refused to speculate about the seriousness of the injury. The 
hospital didn't release any information. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt that he needed me, because I knew his family would want  
me to be there to give them information,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another star receiver, Denver's Shannon Sharpe, broke his left  
collarbone against Oakland. It wasn't immediately known how long 
Sharpe would be sidelined. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin caught a short pass from Troy Aikman in the first quarter,  
tried to shake a tackle from Bobby Taylor and was hit on the head 
by safety Tim Hauck. As Taylor tackled Irvin, Hauck's shoulder pad 
collided with the side of Irvin's helmet, twisting his head 
awkwardly as it hit the artificial turf. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin was scheduled to spend the night in the hospital, then  
return to Dallas on Jones' jet as early as Monday. Cowboys doctor 
Robert Vandermeer said the herniated disc probably was an old 
injury that wasn't caused by the collision. 
</P>
<P>
	Irvin moved his fingers and appeared to be talking as he lay on  
his back for more than 10 minutes. He was fitted with a neck brace 
and loaded onto a stretcher as his teammates circled in prayer 
across the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Many fans at Veterans Stadium cheered when they realized Irvin  
was down. Players on both sides said they were disgusted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know our fans pride themselves on being tough, but that  
wasn't tough,'' Eagles receiver Charles Johnson said. ``That was 
just plain ignorant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas' Emmitt Smith said: ``It disgusted me to death. This is  
just a game. Life, paralyzation and death are a reality. Sport is 
sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Eagles went on to beat the Cowboys 13-10.  
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe was injured in the third quarter against the Raiders,  
adding to the Broncos' long list of serious injuries this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharpe, who has gone to seven consecutive Pro Bowls and is tied  
for first among NFL tight ends with three 1,000-yard receiving 
seasons, was hit by two defenders and landed hard as he attempted 
to catch a pass from Brian Griese. 
</P>
<P>
	The Broncos already are missing running back Terrell Davis and  
linebacker John Mobley for the season. 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis running back Marshall Faulk injured a hip in the first  
quarter of the Rams' 42-20 victory over San Francisco. He returned 
later, but had just 6 yards on seven carries. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same game, 49ers defensive lineman Marvin Washington was  
knocked out for the season with a ruptured quadriceps tendon. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago quarterback Shane Matthews played well in the Bears'  
24-22 victory over Minnesota before pulling his right hamstring 
while scrambling early in the fourth quarter. He completed 19 of 28 
passes for 184 yards, two TDs and no interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	New Orleans quarterback Billy Joe Hobert missed most of Sunday's  
20-17 loss to the Atlanta Falcons after getting a neck stinger on a 
second-quarter sack, the same injury he suffered a week earlier in 
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike last week, when Hobert was carted off, he walked off the  
field Sunday after remaining down for several minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	The battered Detroit defense got more bad news during a 20-10  
loss to San Diego. Starting middle linebacker Stephen Boyd left the 
game with a strained arch, defensive tackle Luther Elliss strained 
his groin and backup linebacker Andre Collins sprained an ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore managed just 246 yards in offense in a 14-11 loss to  
Tennessee as Pro Bowl left tackle Jonathan Ogden missed most of the 
game after straining his neck. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
