<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers' Center Frustrated by Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia Flyers center Rod Brind'Amour  
was depressed and frustrated Sunday while in rehabilitation after a 
second hairline fracture was found in his left foot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I was a day or two away from maybe getting a really  
good practice in, then I find out it's rebroke ... worse than it 
was originally. Now, I'm basically starting all over,'' Brind'Amour 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's real frustrating and depressing watching the team on TV  
and you're not even a part of it being out like this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brind'Amour is expected to be out 3-6 weeks with the second  
fracture, which was discovered in an X-ray at Pennsylvania Hospital 
on Thursday while doctors were checking the recovery of his first 
fracture from a September game. 
</P>
<P>
	Brind'Amour skated in practice Wednesday and thought he was  
getting better. 
</P>
<P>
	``It didn't feel very good, but I just didn't know how much pain  
I was supposed to skate with. I've had other injuries and played 
through them,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Brind'Amour continued his weight training and  
cardiovascular workouts on a stationary bike with a cast on his 
foot, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He sustained the first hairline fracture on Sept. 25 during the  
opening period of the Flyers' 4-2 exhibition loss at New Jersey. He 
was placed on injured reserve Oct. 2, ending the longest 
consecutive-game streak in the NHL. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
