<DOCNO> APW19991010.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 11:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> State Farm Fights Image Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                               *and    	
</P>
<P>
                         *HERBERT G. McCANN    	
</P>
<P>
                      *Associated Press Writers    	
</P>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ill. (AP) -- State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance  
Co., which has long prided itself on customer service, is now in a 
battle to maintain its reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	The insurance company's image took a hit last week when an  
Illinois jury decided the company required the use of inferior auto 
body parts to repair its customers' cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The company acted quickly by announcing it will temporarily  
suspend use of aftermarket auto parts -- which are modeled on 
manufacturers' parts but made without access to factory 
specifications. 
</P>
<P>
	State Farm also had to reassure its employees of the 70-year-old  
company's good intentions. That job fell to Chairman and CEO Edward 
B. Rust, who asserted firmly the insurer is an honest one. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me assure you of something you already know,'' he said  
Friday in speech to managers at the company's Bloomington 
headquarters beamed by satellite to 120 other locations. ``Our 
company did not commit fraud. It's our policy to make sure our 
customers understand that we spify generic parts and that we 
guarantee them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rust spoke only hours before a judge awarded $730 million to  
State Farm policyholders in a class-action lawsuit over the use of 
generic replacement parts in auto-body repairs. Williamson County 
Circuit Judge John Speroni's award was on top of a $456 million 
jury award believed to be the largest ever against an insurance 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say aftermarket parts are not as good as those made for  
automakers. The lawsuit accused State Farm executives of concealing 
that information while flooding customers with brochures promoting 
the parts as a high-quality, low-cost alternative. 
</P>
<P>
	State Farm is the fifth-largest insurer in the country, with  
$24.2 billion in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	In his talk to managers, Rust recounted how years ago the  
company discovered repair shops were using generic parts in place 
of brand name parts to repair claimants' autos. He said the company 
took action in 1987 to assure policyholders were not getting 
cheated. 
</P>
<P>
	``We took the lead in establishing an organization that would  
test parts and certify them if they meet quality standards at least 
as good as the brand name parts,'' he said. ``That organization is 
CAPA, the Certified Auto Parts Association. It exists today, and 
CAPA-certified parts are specified on our repair estimates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rust's pep talk helped ease the concern of at least one of the  
company's 76,500 employees nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we are all concerned about the fact that it (the  
jury's decision) makes us look like maybe we are not doing 
something that's appropriate when really we are,'' said Peggy 
Burton, a supervisor at the company's Bloomington headquarters. ``I 
think its reassuring to hear him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One consumer advocate said any reaction by consumers against  
State Farm would be misplaced. 
</P>
<P>
	Clarence Ditlow, executive director of the Center for Auto  
Safety, a brainchild of consumer advocate Ralph Nader, said State 
Farm deserves credit for its use of generic parts and making 
certain they are of high quality. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the early days the parts weren't very good,'' Ditlow said.  
``Today they are a whole lot better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ditlow said his organization is on the side of State Farm on the  
issue of generic parts, noting that the only other time the 
organization has backed the insurance industry was when it pressed 
for laws requiring auto bumpers to withstand impacts at 5 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Ditlow contends generic auto parts are safe and help lower the  
cost of auto repairs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers should be very upset,'' he said of the jury's  
decision. ``It doesn't matter to the insurer. The consumers will 
pay for this one way or another.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rust said the decision to suspend use of generic parts was  
temporary. And he said the company will appeal the jury's decision 
and the judge's ruling, warning workers it will take years before 
the case is resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had to act quickly,'' Steve Goldstein of the Insurance  
Information Institute, a trade group, said of State Farm's decision 
to stop using generic parts. ``In this day and age, no matter how 
good you are, your reputation can be destroyed very quickly. If 
people think you are not putting safety first, they will move 
quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Goldstein said any negative view of State Farm is  
probably part of an overall lack of good will for the insurance 
industry. He noted policyholders give insurance companies a large 
amount of money in preparation for the worst possible outcome, the 
loss of a home, a car or a family member. 
</P>
<P>
	``That doesn't engender good will,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Because State Farm is a mutual insurance company owned by the  
policyholders and not traded publicly, the only way fallout from 
the jury's decision can be shown is if policies are canceled. 
</P>
<P>
	One analyst says that is unlikely.  
</P>
<P>
	``State Farm is known throughout the industry as a  
consumer-friendly type company,'' said insurance analyst Adam 
Klauber of Cochran, Caronia Securities. He said the jury's decision 
``is definitely a notch against the company. But in reality, it's 
probably not a defining event that will change the public's image 
of the company.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991010.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 22:50:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wineries Complain of Federal Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The purple grapes at the Joseph Phelps  
Vineyards site on the Internet look so moist they might drip off 
the screen. Customers reluctant to trudge to the store can order a 
bottle online from the northern California company. 
</P>
<P>
	But the ease of such direct sales, whether by phone or computer,  
has sparked a constitutional debate in Congress over the 
enforcement of local alcohol laws. Proposed legislation would give 
state authorities the power to ask federal courts to block 
shipments to states where they are outlawed. 
</P>
<P>
	Vintners nationwide are fighting the proposal as an assault on  
the growing Internet portion of their business. Direct sales by 
phone or Internet account for an estimated $500 million of the $17 
billion industry and are crucial to smaller wineries that lack the 
marketing to put their product on store shelves. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, prominent Internet companies oppose the legislation  
as a threat to electronic commerce; supporters deny that. 
</P>
<P>
	The fear is that curtailing wine sales could lead to  
restrictions on other highly regulated products such as cars or 
airline tickets, said Ben Isaacson of the Association for 
Interactive Media, which includes America Online and MCI WorldCom 
as members. 
</P>
<P>
	``This particular piece of legislation could serve as a  
precedent setter,'' Issacson said. 
</P>
<P>
	But without the legislation, state prosecutors say they have  
trouble pursuing charges against out-of-state companies. House and 
Senate conferees are negotiating whether to approve the legislation 
as part of a juvenile-justice bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``This new black market in alcohol is dangerous,'' said the  
sponsor, Rep. Joe Scarborough, R-Fla. ``It is bootlegging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Television news crews in dozens of cases across the country have  
found that teen-agers could buy beer and wine by phone or the 
Internet using their parents' credit cards. Twenty-one state 
attorneys general endorsed the legislation as a way to end that 
access. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not asking for any new federal laws regarding the  
transportation or distribution of alcohol; we are merely asking for 
the power to enforce our own state laws already on the books,'' 
said Virginia Attorney General Mark Earley. 
</P>
<P>
	But vintners were skeptical of any widespread criminal activity.  
Internet brands tend to cost more than bottles at the corner store 
and delivery takes days, making impatient youths unlikely 
customers, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just doesn't happen,'' said Tom Shelton, president of  
Phelps Vineyards in St. Helena, Calif., which sells 10 percent of 
its 100,000 cases a year via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	California has allowed wine shipments to its residents for 36  
years. Of 10,000 complaints investigated each year about minors 
trying to buy alcohol, the state Department of Alcoholic Beverage 
Control received only one involving an attempt to buy through the 
mail, said Manuel Espinoza, the agency's chief deputy director. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms already has  
the power to revoke the license of a winery or distillery if the 
company violates a state's liquor laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Vintners contend the proposed legislation, coupled with  
stiffened local penalties, will scare producers off the Internet. 
Five states already outlaw interstate shipments and 23 others 
prohibit shipment by common carriers such as Federal Express or 
United Parcel Service. 
</P>
<P>
	``These rules are manipulated at the local level,'' Shelton  
said. ``That's very dangerous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not so, according to David Dickerson, spokesman for the Wine and  
Spirits Wholesalers of America. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not because legislators are interested in protecting  
wholesalers; what they're protecting is the ability to enforce 
their laws,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the dispute boils down to a squabble within the  
industry. Since Prohibition ended, states have strictly regulated 
alcohol sales so that producers sell to wholesalers, who sell to 
retailers, who sell to consumers. The Internet allows wineries to 
bypass wholesalers and retailers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think Congress has any business helping liquor  
distributors get away with monopolizing the business,'' said Rep. 
George Radanovich, R-Calif., who owns a winery. ``I view it as a 
direct assault on the Internet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wineries complain that under the system they can't get on store  
shelves, as the number of wholesalers has plummeted from 11,000 to 
300 in the last four decades. At the same time, the number of 
wineries grew from 375 to 1,800, with nearly half in California and 
producing 90 percent of the country's wine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sheer arithmetic tells you a retail store cannot possibly have  
even the shelf space to offer more than a mere sample of this 
multitude of American wines,'' said Sen. Dianne Feinstein, 
D-Calif., who opposes the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress should be working to promote and encourage electronic  
commerce, not taking steps which could stifle and chill its 
growth,'' she said. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991010.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 09:30:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dispute Over Minority Judges Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The volatile mix of ideology, politics and  
race has given new prominence to the long-simmering dispute between 
the White House and the Republican Senate over confirmation of 
President Clinton's choices for federal judgeships. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Senate rejected a black nominee for the federal bench  
on a strict party-line vote, Clinton called the action a disgrace. 
And he did not let the matter drop. He repeated his criticism over 
the weekend in a speech to a Hispanic group and cited the case of 
Richard Paez, a Mexican-American, nominated for a federal appeals 
court vacancy more than three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am deeply dissatisfied with the Senate's partisan handling  
of some of my minority nominees,'' Clinton said at the annual 
meeting of the national Hispanic Leadership Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans angrily counter that race has not been a factor in  
the holdup of the Paez nomination or the rejection of the 
nomination of Ronnie White, the first black to sit on the Missouri 
Supreme Court, for a federal judgeship. Nominated by Clinton 27 
months ago, White was turned down on a 54-45 vote -- all Republicans 
voting to reject the nomination and all Democrats supporting it. 
</P>
<P>
	White's detractors, led by Missouri's two Republican senators,  
argued he was opposed by law enforcement groups because he had too 
often dissented on death penalty rulings. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri law enforcement officers, said Sen. John Ashcroft,  
R-Mo., ``are entitled to judges who will enforce the law as it is 
written, and not reach for loopholes that benefit criminals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Angry Democrats, however, said Republicans had distorted White's  
record on capital punishment. Senate Democratic leader Tom Daschle 
of South Dakota called it a ``dark day'' in the Senate. ``The vote 
tells minority judicial candidates, 'do not apply.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott, R-Miss., shot back that Clinton had ``impugned the  
integrity'' of the Senate and ``should be ashamed'' of his 
suggestion that race played a part in GOP votes. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate's second-ranked Republican, Sen. Don Nickles of  
Oklahoma, asked whether Democrats had applied a ``color test'' in 
1991 when they voted against Clarence Thomas' nomination to the 
Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech to the Hispanic Leadership Conference, Clinton  
alluded to the political stakes when he told the group that America 
increasingly ``will look like you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To warm applause, Clinton said Saturday that Hispanics are  
moving quickly ``into the mainstream of American life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The national Hispanic population of 31 million is expected to  
overtake the non-Hispanic black population to become the largest 
minority group by the end of 2004. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats have long contended that Republicans use political  
stalling tactics to keep Clinton nominees off the federal bench, 
and that minority and women nominees have fared the worst. 
Republicans respond that trouble occurs only when Clinton nominates 
candidates who are unacceptably liberal. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats cite recent findings by the bipartisan Constitution  
Project that the Senate during the 1997-98 session took an average 
186 days either to accept or reject white nominees, but 246 days 
for minorities. Moreover, the rejection rate was 14 percent for the 
92 white, and 35 percent for the 31 minority nominees. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, after a stormy debate, Frederica Massiah-Jackson  
withdrew her nomination to be the first black woman to sit on the 
federal bench in Philadelphia just days before a Senate vote she 
was likely to lose. Senate Republicans said she was soft on crime. 
</P>
<P>
	Wade Henderson of the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights said  
that while minorities and women may face obstacles because they 
tend to be more liberal than the average white male judge, there 
still ``appears to be a double standard'' in the Senate's handling 
of nominees such as White. 
</P>
<P>
	Just before the White vote, Latino groups joined Democrats to  
demand action on two nominees to the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals, 
Paez and San Francisco attorney Marsha Berzon. Paez has been in 
limbo longer than any other nominee, and Berzon since January 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the Judiciary Committee chairman  
responsible for moving judge nominations through the Senate, noted 
that 45 percent of the judicial nominees reported to the Senate 
floor this year have been women or minorities. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991010.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 15:40:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Austria, Haider Seek Common Ground </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Austria's interior minister strayed from  
his Social Democratic Party's assurances against forming a 
coalition with the far right-wing Freedom Party, saying instead 
that there may be common ground between the two parties. 
</P>
<P>
	Interior Minister Karl Schloegl told the news magazine Format in  
an issue due on newsstands Monday that the gulf between his party 
and that of conservative Joerg Haider may not be so wide to 
preclude working together. 
</P>
<P>
	``In politics, nothing can be permanently shut out,'' Schloegl  
was quoted as saying. ``I am, however, skeptical that (Haider) 
personally is acceptable to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since last weekend's national election, in which the  
anti-immigrant Freedom Party won 27 percent of the vote, the Social 
Democrats have vehemently denied that they would consider forming a 
coalition with Haider's group. 
</P>
<P>
	Most exit polls show that the constituency of Haider, son of a  
Nazi party member, is young working-class men who fear that EU 
expansion and a liberal immigration policy will cost them their 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Freedom Party campaign included in its platform restricted  
immigration. Some of the party's election posters were criticized 
as being blatantly anti-foreigner. 
</P>
<P>
	With the counting of votes still incomplete, the Freedom Party  
is competing closely for second place with the conservative 
Austrian Peoples Party -- until now the junior coalition partner 
with the Social Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Counting of absentee votes will decide final placings, but the  
People's Party has threatened to go into opposition should it 
finish third. The final result is expected Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Schloegl also criticized the opposition Greens and Liberal Forum  
parties for escalating the debate on hostility toward foreigners by 
campaigning for more openness concerning the case of a Nigerian 
illegal immigrant who died while with two Austrian policemen and 
while being deported. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigations revealed that the man's mouth had been sealed  
with adhesive tape and that he died of suffocation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Schloegl has apparently still not grasped that human rights  
are indivisible,'' the Austria Press Agency quoted senior Greens 
official Madeleine Petrovic as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whoever ignores this connection, and the truth about how the  
Freedom Party's mannerisms rotate, is preparing themselves for a 
coalition with Haider.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991010.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 16:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
