<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Drug To Treat Stress Disorder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *BY PHIL GALEWITZ   	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After watching one of his firemen die in the  
line of duty, fire Chief John Soave became withdrawn, had trouble 
sleeping and was bothered by flashbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors diagnosed him with post-traumatic stress disorder, a  
psychiatric condition once associated only with combat veterans, 
but now known to affect millions of people who experience car 
accidents, sexual assaults and other horrible incidents. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of his treatment, Soave was prescribed Zoloft, a drug  
first approved in 1992 for depression. 
</P>
<P>
	``It helped calm me down,'' said Soave, of Stoughton, Mass.,  
whose been taking Pfizer's once-a-day pill for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on its early success, Zoloft later this year is expected  
to become the first prescription medication specifically approved 
by the federal government for post-traumatic stress. 
</P>
<P>
	A Food and Drug Administration advisory panel on Friday approved  
the drug's expanded labeling, and the agency usually follows its 
advice. However, despite Soave's success, panelists cautioned the 
drug so far seems to help only women, not men with the anxiety 
disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	Health experts say the approval will be both symbolic-- by  
drawing more attention and perhaps research dollars to the disorder 
-- and it will have the practical effect of leading more doctors to 
prescribe the medication and make patients more accepting of it. 
</P>
<P>
	It is estimated that about 7 percent of Americans will suffer  
from post traumatic stress at some point in their life. 
</P>
<P>
	Psychiatrists, who believe Zoloft makes patients more amenable  
to the counseling necessary to overcome their disorder, say the FDA 
approval would help increase awareness of the disease that often 
goes untreated. That's because drug companies like Pfizer typically 
spend heavily educating consumers and doctors about a condition 
once they win expanded labeling. 
</P>
<P>
	After the FDA approves a drug for one disease, doctors can  
prescribe it for any purpose, though pharmaceutical firms can only 
market it for the specific condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Mental health experts applaud Pfizer's attempt to get the  
additional FDA approval for Zoloft. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pfizer has its own motivations.  
</P>
<P>
	Zoloft is Pfizer's second leading selling drug, behind blood  
pressure pill Norvasc. Zoloft, which is expected to record $2.1 
billion in sales this year, is locked in a battle with several 
other antidepressants including Eli Lilly's top seller Prozac and 
SmithKline Beecham's Paxil, which is a close third. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the three drugs are similar, the companies have tried to  
differentiate them by getting approved for conditions beyond 
depression. SmithKline, for example, this summer won federal 
approval to market Paxil to treat social phobia or extreme shyness. 
Eli Lilly is seeking FDA approval to market Prozac for the most 
severe form of premenstrual syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	Expanding the uses of an existing drug is one of the most common  
methods pharmaceutical firms use to build profits. It's 
considerably cheaper and less risky than developing a new drug. 
</P>
<P>
	The expanded labeling should give a small boost to Zoloft sales,  
said Alex Zisson, a securities analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. More 
significantly, he said, it will help Pfizer improve its ties with 
psychiatrists. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good way to keep the thought leaders in the psychiatric  
community happy with the company,'' Zisson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Patients who suffer from post-traumatic stress experience a wide  
variety of symptoms including nightmares, flashbacks and intrusive 
recollections -- patients think about the events that caused the 
trauma even though they don't want to. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts stress Zoloft helps with the symptoms but is not a cure.  
Only counseling helps patients get over the trauma. Women are more 
likely than men to develop the condition, though researchers are 
not sure why. 
</P>
<P>
	``The drug is quite helpful,'' said Dr. Bessl vanderKolk, a  
psychiatrist at Boston University. ``It helps people to be less 
there and more here; it helps people live in the present and be 
less overwhelmed by their past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A study of 187 post traumatic stress patients found that those  
who took Zoloft had significantly fewer symptoms than those taking 
a dummy pill, according to a report presented at the American 
Psychiatric Association meeting earlier this year. Patients had 
fewer feelings of hopelessness and memory impairment. 
</P>
<P>
	The most common side effect shown in the studies was insomnia  
and dry mouth. The study was funded by Pfizer. 
</P>
<P>
	Soave, who resigned as fire chief in January 1998, was not a  
part of the study. He said Zoloft and counseling have helped him 
deal with the emotional toll of the fatal fire that occurred in 
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``It never goes away, but the impact is much lower than what it  
was.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
