<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colt To End Consumer Handgun Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Colt's Manufacturing Company will  
virtually stop taking orders for commercial handguns before the 
month is over, Newsweek reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing industry sources it did not name, the newsmagazine said  
in editions that hit newsstands Monday that the West Hartford-based 
gunmaker also will lay off as many as 300 of its 700 union workers 
in Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven Sliwa, president and chief executive of Colt's, could not  
be reached for comment by The Associated Press. A telephone message 
was left at his home Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling Colt's the biggest victim of lawsuits filed against the  
gun industry, Newsweek reported that the cash-squeezed company is 
having trouble paying its vendors and hopes to avoid the damage of 
a possible jury verdict by abandoning the handgun business -- at 
least for now. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to focus on what we know we can make money on, without  
taking that risk,'' a Colt's executive told Newsweek. ``It's 
extremely painful when you have to withdraw from a business for 
irrational reasons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colt's will keep making military and collectible guns, which are  
the bulk of its business, Newsweek reported. And its new startup 
company -- iColt -- plans to market a ``smart gun,'' which can be 
fired only by the owner, sometime next year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
