<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Georgia Had Odd Gov. Race in 1947 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The dead voted, one ``governor'' was hanged in  
effigy, another tried to rule from a Capitol information desk, the 
state seal disappeared and national magazines sneered. 
</P>
<P>
	For 63 days, until a court ruling settled the matter, three men  
-- all Democrats -- laid claim to the Georgia governor's office in 
1947. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia politics in the 1940s were sport and entertainment.  
</P>
<P>
	One of the most flamboyant figures was Eugene Talmadge, who by  
1946 had already served three terms as governor. He was not in 
office that year, but was itching to return. 
</P>
<P>
	His previous terms had provided endless cracker barrel debate  
over such things as the time he declared martial law around the 
Capitol and used armed security men to establish his power over a 
recalcitrant highway department. 
</P>
<P>
	His evangelical-style stump speeches promised low taxes, small  
government, white supremacy, a $3 car tag and special benefits for 
veterans. 
</P>
<P>
	But Talmadge was 62 and ailing. As a contingency, people close  
to him quietly mobilized a write-in campaign for his 33-year-old 
son, Herman. 
</P>
<P>
	They were banking on a provision of the Georgia Constitution  
which stipulated that if no ``person'' won a majority vote, the 
Legislature would choose a governor from among the other leading 
candidates. They theorized that if Eugene Talmadge died, he could 
not be considered a person. 
</P>
<P>
	Talmadge easily won -- and died Dec. 21, before taking office.  
</P>
<P>
	His son claimed the governorship.  
</P>
<P>
	But M.E. Thompson, who had just been elected Georgia's first  
lieutenant governor, said he should become acting governor. And 
incumbent Gov. Ellis Arnall announced he would relinquish the 
office only to Thompson. 
</P>
<P>
	On Jan. 14, the Legislature met to canvass the vote and found  
that, out of three candidates, Herman Talmadge was third. 
</P>
<P>
	But then the canvassers turned up 58 more write-in votes for  
Talmadge from Telfair County, the Talmadge home. 
</P>
<P>
	Talmadge was elected governor by the Legislature and went to  
claim the office from Arnall. 
</P>
<P>
	Jimmy Bentley, a young Talmadge volunteer, was a witness to the  
proceedings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ellis came out and Talmadge said to him, `I've come to claim  
the governor's office.' Ellis says to him, `I don't accept this. I 
consider you an impostor,''' Bentley recalled. ``Talmadge said, 
`Thank you,' and turned and instructed a state trooper to be sure 
that Arnall got to his home safely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Time magazine reported the pro-Talmadge crowd charged the door  
and an Arnall aide's jaw was broken. 
</P>
<P>
	The next day, the two men sat 20 feet apart, Arnall in his  
office and Talmadge in an anteroom. 
</P>
<P>
	When Arnall left for the night, Talmadge had the office locks  
changed. So the next morning, Arnall commandeered an information 
desk in the Capitol rotunda and governed from there. 
</P>
<P>
	Within a few days, Arnall resigned in favor of Thompson but  
Talmadge still occupied the office. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even the South had never seen anything quite like the  
Caesarean operation by which Hummon (for the Georgian pronunciation 
of Herman) was jerked out of obscurity ... and installed in the 
governor's mansion in his pappy's place,'' said Time magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	There were lawsuits and protests. University students hanged  
Talmadge in effigy. 
</P>
<P>
	The state seal, needed for official documents, couldn't be  
found. Secretary of State Ben Fortson later revealed he had hidden 
it beneath the seat of his wheelchair because he didn't know who 
was governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, The Atlanta Journal hit the streets with the headline  
``Telfair Dead Were Voted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 58 late Telfair County votes, 34 had been cast in  
alphabetical order, some of the alleged voters had been dead for 
years, and some of the living said they hadn't gone to the polls. 
</P>
<P>
	No one ever was prosecuted for voter fraud. Talmadge wrote in  
his 1987 autobiography that he never told his workers to steal 
votes. 
</P>
<P>
	On March 19, the state Supreme Court said Talmadge supporters  
had misconstrued the Constitution, and ruled 5-2 that Thompson was 
head of state until a special election could be held for the 
remainder of Eugene Talmadge's term. 
</P>
<P>
	The special election was held Sept. 8, 1948, and Herman Talmadge  
won. He was elected to a full term in 1950, then ran successfully 
for the Senate in 1956, serving until 1980 when he was defeated 
after being denounced by the Senate Ethics Committee for 
mismanagement of his office finances. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19991010.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 14:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lone Star State Laments Texas Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	While New Yorkers dream of a Subway Series, fans in the Lone  
Star State can only lament of what might have been. 
</P>
<P>
	Hopes for an I-45 World Series or maybe a fourth Texas vs. New  
York championship series this year were squashed over the weekend 
when the Houston Astros and Texas Rangers were eliminated from the 
first round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	In case you're counting, that makes them 0-for-ever in playoff  
series. 
</P>
<P>
	Good karma was the best reason to think 1999 would be different.  
</P>
<P>
	After all, the Dallas Stars won their first Stanley Cup, the San  
Antonio Spurs won their first NBA title and the Houston Comets 
ruled the WNBA for the third time in the league's three years. And 
don't forget the individual achievements of Lance Armstrong and 
Michael Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers roared into the postseason with 95 wins, their most  
ever, and one of the most potent offenses in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	They limped out by scoring a grand total of one run in three  
losses to the New York Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas lost 3-0 in the finale Saturday night, extending the  
club's playoff losing streak to nine straight -- all to the Yankees. 
Home fans have yet to see the Rangers win a postseason game in four 
tries. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no jinx,'' Rafael Palmeiro of the Rangers said. ``We  
just didn't do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just getting to the playoffs was impressive enough considering  
all the injuries and illness the Astros endured along the way to 
their third straight NL Central title. 
</P>
<P>
	After splitting two games in Atlanta, there was hope Friday that  
Houston would go up 2-1 in the best-of-5 series. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Braves held off a bases-loaded, no-outs jam and won 5-3  
in 12 innings, then won 7-5 Saturday in what turned out to be the 
final baseball game in the Astrodome. 
</P>
<P>
	The Astros will play outdoors, on grass at Enron Field next  
year. Maybe that will change their luck. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a winning team,'' first baseman Jeff Bagwell said.  
``We'll come through sooner or later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even the biggest optimist in the Lone Star State knew the odds  
were heavily against an all-Texas World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	But it would have been fitting for one of them to make the  
League Championship Series against either the New York's Mets or 
Yankees considering the NHL, NBA and WNBA championships were fought 
between teams from Texas and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Alas, with no chance for Texas to win a fourth pro sports title,  
there's only one thing left for Texans to root for: a fourth finals 
loss by a New York team. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
