<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Michigan State Fans Revel in Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Exhilarated Michigan State fans  
celebrated their team's victory over Michigan without a major 
ruckus. 
</P>
<P>
	East Lansing police processed 41 people through city jail  
between 7 p.m. Saturday and 6 a.m. Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say it was a typical home-football night,'' said East  
Lansing police Lt. John Benson. ``It was busy but nothing 
horrendous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartans upset the visiting Wolverines, 34-31.  
</P>
<P>
	As of about 6 p.m. Saturday, police had issued about 150  
tickets, largely for minors possessing alcohol, disorderly conduct 
and public urination, state police Capt. Tony Kleibecker said. 
State police could not provide an updated figure Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, more than 125 people were charged in riots that  
followed the Michigan State basketball team's loss to Duke in the 
NCAA Final Four. The riots caused an estimated $238,000 in damages 
with eight cars torched and 24 windows broken in downtown 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compared to that, it was a cakewalk,'' Benson said.  
</P>
<P>
	Michigan State campus police said there were arrests on campus,  
but would not release the number. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
