<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.J. Wins Qtr. of Brennan Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Calling the disgraced penny-stock tycoon a  
``big crook,'' a Superior Court judge ordered Robert Brennan to pay 
25 percent of his income to the state. 
</P>
<P>
	The amount, which Brennan's bankruptcy attorney argued was  
excessive, will go toward paying the $45 million Brennan owes from 
a settlement of stock fraud charges reached earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why is that excessive?'' Superior Court Judge Philip M.  
Freedman asked on Friday. ``I mean, this man spent $3,000 in a 
liquor store last month.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Looking over a state-supplied list of Brennan's ``lifestyle  
expenditures'' for June and July -- the list includes a $2,829.10 at 
the Spring Lake Bottle Shop; more than $1,900 in fees at three golf 
courses; and $586.71 at Brielle Florist -- Freedman continued, ``The 
only bill I see here that the average person pays is a payment to 
Allstate Insurance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan did not appear in court on Friday. Messages that were  
left for his attorney, Gerald H. Gline, and for Brennan at the Due 
Process Golf Club on Saturday were not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	According to court documents, Brennan earns about $388,000 per  
year as a consultant at the Due Process Golf Club in Colts Neck. 
The property, now a golf course, is owned in a partnership between 
Brennan and his three adult sons. 
</P>
<P>
	The state had filed a motion this week to recoup some of the $45  
million Brennan owes from the settlement he signed in June with the 
state Bureau of Securities to avoid a criminal trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The money is to compensate the investors state regulators  
believe Brennan swindled. In the settlement, Brennan denied 
wrongdoing, but consented to a finding that he used ``substantial 
influence'' at two brokerages to make ``unreasonably excessive 
profits'' in low-cost stocks in which he held an undisclosed 
interest from 1988-95. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to granting New Jersey's request for a quarter of  
Brennan's income, Freedman also said he will grant the state 
$18,000 from one of Brennan's bank accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Brennan, 56, became nationally known in the 1980s through  
television commercials for his First Jersey Securities Inc. in 
which he stepped from a helicopter and told investors to ``come 
grow with us.'' The company has been inactive since 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	He declared bankruptcy in 1995, when a federal judge in New York  
ruled that he cheated First Jersey investors and ordered him to pay 
what is now more than $78 million to the Securities and Exchange 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite the bankruptcy and judgments against him, Freedman  
said Brennan ``still lives at a standard of living that any other 
person, other than a few, would be happy to have.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
