<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Oct. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Bosnian Serbs May Withdraw Lawsuit  
</P>
<P>
	BANJA LUKA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- The Bosnian Serb Assembly  
on Sunday endorsed a proposal to withdraw a lawsuit against 
Yugoslavia for aggression and genocide in connection with the 
1992-95 ethnic war here. The case was filed by the Sarajevo 
government six years ago in the World Court in The Hague. At the 
time, the government was Muslim-dominated. Now, the Bosnian Serbs 
want to withdraw the suit. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Expected To Reject Key Points in Peace Plan  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russia is expected to reject several key  
points of Chechnya President Aslan Maskhadov's proposed peace plan 
brought forth Sunday to end the fighting in his breakaway republic. 
Russia did not respond immediately, but will likely reject the 
withdrawal of Russian forces, which entered Chechnya two weeks ago. 
Maskhadov said the two sides should observe the basic principles of 
a peace accord that ended the 1994-96 Checen war. 

</P>
<P>
	Portugal's Ruling Socialists Return to Power  
</P>
<P>
	LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Buoyed by a robust economy and a  
confident mood among many Portuguese, the governing Socialist Party 
was returned to power by a comfortable margin in the country's 
general election Sunday. The Socialist Party won 44 percent of the 
vote, according to official results and with more than 95 percent 
of ballots counted. 

</P>
<P>
	Vigil Honoring Gay Student's Death Draws 600  
</P>
<P>
	LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- About 600 people gathered Sunday night for  
a candelight vigil honoring Matthew Shepard, the gay college 
student who was fatally beaten and tied to a post a year ago. One 
of two men accused in the slaying, Aaron McKinney, 22, goes on 
trial Monday on charges of first-degree murder, kidnapping and 
aggravated robbery. 

</P>
<P>
	Officials Discuss Chinese WTO Entry  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Top trade officials from China and the European  
Union on Sunday discussed China's bid to join the World Trade 
Organization. Pascal Lamy, the new EU trade commissioner, said 
after the meeting that he hopes EU-Chinese trade negotiations will 
now resume. He gave no date, though. Discussions were suspended 
after NATO's May 7 bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade 
during the alliance's air war on Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Group Can't Agree on Endorsement  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- A grass-roots conservative Republican  
organization today failed to agree on which GOP presidential 
candidate it would endorse. The first National Federation of 
Republican Assemblies convention ended with a vote in which 
publisher Steve Forbes got 164 votes, or 62.4 percent, with Pat 
Buchanan getting 99 votes, or 37.6 percent. But Forbes fell short 
of the group's by-law requiring a two-thirds majority for NFRA 
endorsement. The three-day NFRA convention in Kansas City drew 274 
delegates from 33 states. 

</P>
<P>
	UFCW Labor Union Backs Gore  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The board of the United Food and Commercial  
Workers voted unanimously today to put its 1.4 million members 
behind Vice President Al Gore in his bid for the Democratic 
presidential nomination. The endorsement came at the urging of John 
Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO labor federation, who met 
privately with the UFCW board today to press Gore's case. 
Presidents of the AFL-CIO's biggest unions, including the UFCW, 
will vote to recommend the federation's overall endorsement, which 
in turn will be decided by all 68 member unions. 

</P>
<P>
	'Double Jeopardy' No. 1 At Box Office  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Double Jeopardy,'' the film about a wife  
done wrong, took in $13.6 million to remain the No. 1 movie for the 
third straight weekend, according to estimates today. ``Random 
Hearts,'' with Harrison Ford and Kristin Scott Thomas, debuted in 
second place with $13.1 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Sprewell Explains Absence From Camp  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Latrell Sprewell finally offered a feeble  
explanation today for missing the first week of training camp, and 
the New York Knicks decided to bench him for their first exhibition 
game. Sprewell said he had simply ignored the Knicks' phone 
messages as he drove across the country, doing a 36-hour stretch 
solo from Oakland to Milwaukee. As for ignoring calls from the 
Knicks, who were wondering what he was doing, he said, ``That's 
what agents are for.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KELLY GRUEL  































  	   	
