<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Premier: Breakup a Mistake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) -- Czech Premier Milos Zeman says the  
1993 breakup of Czechoslovakia was an ``irreversible mistake,'' the 
newspaper Lidove Noviny reported in its weekend edition. 
</P>
<P>
	The Czechoslovak federation broke up peacefully on Jan 1, 1993,  
after Slovakia demanded more autonomy from the federal capital in 
Prague. Known as the ``velvet divorce,'' it was the subject of 
bitter debate not only between the two sides but also within the 
Czech and Slovak areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Zeman, who criticized the split at the time, met with Slovak  
Premier Mikolas Dzurinda in Prague on Thursday. He said the 
complicated process of working out a financial settlement should be 
final by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	There is little friction over the issue today, but looking back,  
Zeman called the breakup a mistake. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a decision that cannot be taken back and despite that I  
call it a mistake ... a mistake that is irreversible,'' he told the 
paper. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether the Czech Republic and its people would be better  
off in a still-federal Czechoslovakia, Zeman said, ``from a 
geopolitical point of view that is certainly so,'' but added that 
he supported Slovakia's membership in NATO as soon as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	When the nations were splitting, Zeman had sought a confederal  
arrangement that both the Czech and Slovak governments considered 
unfeasible. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
