<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Commercial Satellite Reaches Orbit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- A Ukrainian-Russian rocket carrying a  
U.S. satellite roared off a launch platform in the Pacific, the 
first commercial liftoff for the Sea Launch Co., an international 
consortium led by Boeing. 
</P>
<P>
	The 200-foot-tall Zenit-3SL rocket rose off the oceangoing  
platform late Saturday at a point near the equator, carrying the 
7,600-pound satellite for DirecTV. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was beautiful,'' said Anne Eisele, a Boeing spokeswoman who  
watched from Sea Launch headquarters in Long Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	The self-propelled launch pad, accompanied by a support ship, is  
a former oil drilling platform. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the Earth moves faster at the equator, rockets launched  
there have an advantage in reaching orbit with heavier payloads. 
</P>
<P>
	The DirecTV satellite reached geosynchronous orbit, one that  
keeps it over the same place on Earth, about 62 minutes after 
liftoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Sea Launch has orders for 19 more launches through 2003.  
</P>
<P>
	The company's partners are Boeing Commercial Space Co. of Kent,  
Wash.; Norwegian ship builder Kvaerner Maritime; Russia's RSC 
Energia, and Ukrainian rocket maker KB Yuzhnoye/PO Yuzhmash. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ukrainian company provides the first two stages of the  
rocket and Energia builds the upper stage. Boeing performs the 
spacecraft integration. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
