<DOCNO> APW19991010.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 23:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Battle Brews Over Slot Machines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) -- When it comes to gambler-enticing  
graphics and animation on slot machines, state regulators say 
cartoon flirt Betty Boop might be OK -- but a ``South Park'' theme 
is just too kid-friendly. 
</P>
<P>
	So Nevada officials are considering a rule to ban artwork based  
on cartoons, comic strip superheroes or other images that suggest 
slots are child's play. 
</P>
<P>
	While some slot makers say it's a Mickey Mouse idea, Gaming  
Control Board Chairman Steve DuCharme says the plan stems from 
genuine concern over marketing that goes too far in targeting 
minors. 
</P>
<P>
	``The manufacturers have been reporting to us that they've been  
seeking licensing arrangements for various cartoon characters -- 
Saturday morning cartoon characters that no adult I know watches,'' 
said DuCharme. ``I don't know how you justify having a Saturday 
morning cartoon character as your theme on a gaming device.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We think developing a new customer base is fine -- as long as  
they're all over 21 years of age,'' DuCharme said. Twenty-one is 
the legal age to gamble in Nevada. 
</P>
<P>
	Themed slots aren't new. Some already in casinos feature  
graphics or animation based on Monopoly, Yahtzee, Elvis Presley and 
1930s icon Betty Boop. 
</P>
<P>
	New slots in the works are based on the Pink Panther, ``I Dream  
of Jeannie,'' ``The Munsters,'' ``The Three Stooges'' and other TV 
or movie hits. There's even one slot topped by a dancing toy 
chicken. Others have full-size heads of Lurch and Uncle Fester from 
``The Addams Family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DuCharme started thinking about a limit on slot themes when he  
saw a proposed machine based on ``South Park'' cartoon characters. 
He also fretted about suggested devices that featured comic book 
superheroes. 
</P>
<P>
	All slot machine designs must be approved by the three-member  
Gaming Control Board. Until now, themes haven't been a big issue, 
and new game approvals typically have taken only a few minutes out 
of lengthy agendas at monthly public meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	Without a uniform standard on slot themes, DuCharme said the  
board and its testing laboratory must make case-by-case 
determinations on each slot concept that's presented. The lab 
staffers' main job is to check out inner workings of slots to 
ensure the games give players a chance to win and aren't vulnerable 
to cheaters. 
</P>
<P>
	With a standard, ``it doesn't fall on the lab manager or one  
person on the Control Board to say 'I think Mr. Magoo is OK but I 
think Teletubbies is not OK' -- without some way of articulating 
what the difference is,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian McKay of Reno-based International Game Technology, the  
world's leading slot manufacturer, is against the board's proposal, 
which is to be discussed at a hearing in Las Vegas on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't say it's ridiculous,'' McKay said. ``But there's no  
need for such a regulation because the Control Board already has 
the authority to OK any game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``And our games are not designed for children by definition,''  
McKay adds. ``Slot machines are designed, developed and marketed 
for adults.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed regulation is pitting more than just the industry  
types against the regulators. There are also some differences among 
members of the Nevada Gaming Commission, which will have final say 
on any rule that the Control Board approves. 
</P>
<P>
	While a majority of the commission favored the board's plan for  
hearings on the proposed regulation, Commissioner Augie Gurrola is 
against the idea. He agrees with the industry argument that the 
state already has the power to reject any slot motif that is deemed 
unsuitable. 
</P>
<P>
	IGT pulled back its ``South Park'' slot because of the Control  
Board's concerns, but is going ahead with other concepts such as 
``The Addams Family'' slot, subject to a final endorsement from the 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooke Dunn of Las Vegas-based Shuffle Master, currently testing  
its Three Stooges slot, thinks that regulators should avoid what 
could turn into a drawn-out process of setting standards for slot 
themes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a Mickey Mouse regulation because it's not  
necessary,'' Dunn said. ``This is a very competitive market these 
days. If it's not geared to adults, if it doesn't fit an adult 
image, they're not going to play the game and it won't stay on the 
casino floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dunn also questions why slot machines are singled out. He says  
major hotel-casinos in Las Vegas are not hassled because of their 
use of themes designed, in part, to bring in families. 
</P>
<P>
	``What about the big clown that's been in front of Circus Circus  
for 25 years? What about Treasure Island? Isn't that a children's 
story?'' he asked. ``What about the MGM and its Wizard of Oz theme? 
Lions and tigers and bears, oh my!'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
