<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 14:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penn State Looks for Improvement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Indiana has been dealt with. Iowa has  
been tossed aside. Now it starts getting serious for Penn State in 
the Big Ten. 
</P>
<P>
	A 31-7 victory over Iowa on Saturday got the No. 2-ranked  
Nittany Lions warmed up for what's ahead, starting with Ohio State 
next Saturday at home. They also have games left with Purdue, 
Michigan and Michigan State, along with Illinois and Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a tough stretch and it comes after Penn State (6-0  
overall, 2-0 Big Ten) had trouble putting away an Iowa team that's 
last in the league in offense and looked helpless a week earlier in 
a 49-3 loss at Michigan State. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a lot to work on still,'' quarterback Kevin Thompson  
said. ``Every week, no matter how good we win or how much we win 
by, we're always going to have something we're going to work on and 
focus on the following week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's plenty to focus on with what's coming up. At Iowa (1-4,  
0-2), Penn State led only 14-7 midway through the third quarter. It 
took a 47-yard touchdown run by Eric McCoo, a goal line stand and a 
key penalty for the Nittany Lions to break it open. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to get better -- a lot better -- and quick,''  
linebacker LaVar Arrington said. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State did run the ball better than it has all year, rushing  
for 341 yards, but it wasn't until the fourth quarter that the 
Nittany Lions had success running straight ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Before that, they got most of their yardage on McCoo's run,  
Eddie Drummond's 68-yard touchdown run on a reverse and No. 2 
quarterback Rashard Casey's scrambling. McCoo finished with 130 
yards on 13 carries. Casey had 65 yards in eight attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We ran the same plays we've been running,'' McCoo said. ``We  
just executed better. I got more yardage. I ran more. There were 
bigger holes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other than two interceptions and a missed field goal, Penn State  
coach Joe Paterno found little to harp about. 
</P>
<P>
	``Against Michigan State, they got behind so fast, it was 21-0,  
10 minutes into the game,'' Paterno said. ``They didn't get a 
chance to show much. So it was tough to figure out what we were 
going to get. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew they had a couple of good backs. I thought their  
quarterback played a heck of a football game. I kept telling our 
guys, `He's going to throw one to us, he's going to throw one to 
us' and he didn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Iowa quarterback Randy Reiners completed 18-of-30 passes for 192  
yards and a touchdown with no interceptions. He was sacked four 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about time,'' said Penn State linebacker Brandon Short.  
``We started getting some of that pressure like we used to get back 
in the good old days. I think we confused them a little bit with 
our blitzes. We ran a few different things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Short made a big play when he hauled Reiners down by the ankle  
on fourth-and-goal at the Penn State 2-yard line on the first play 
of the fourth quarter. A touchdown would have cut the lead to 
21-14. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overall I'm pleased,'' Paterno said. ``I think that was a good  
win for us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
