<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Intranet Links Colo. Telecommunity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Beginning next spring, Jon Lowry will be able to  
wake up, switch on his computer and get the results of last night's 
neighborhood Little League game. 
</P>
<P>
	He also could get a reminder about his turn for the car pool,  
check out a library book or even send a request to the area 
pharmacist to refill his prescription. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowry is a resident of one of the nation's first  
telecommunities, which links businesses, residents, schools and 
government offices via an intranet system, a computer Web site 
available to a smaller number of users. 
</P>
<P>
	The community's high-speed telecommunications system already  
allows Lowry, 51, an Advanced Digital Information Corp. executive, 
to work from home, transferring data at nearly 100 times the speed 
of a regular modem. Eventually, he will be able do video 
conferencing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great,'' Lowry said. ``When I do work from home, it  
certainly has made me more productive. No more dial-up, no more 
messing with the modem or having to wait to get connected. I log in 
once, and then I'm online all day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The telecommunity has been constructed on property at a former  
Air Force base in eastern Denver that coincidentally shares Lowry's 
name. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 200 homes are connected to a digital broadband  
fiber-to-the-curb network and, within the next five years to seven 
years, 4,000 homes and apartments will be connected to the 
Intranet. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowry also will link an office park, several schools and  
businesses to the intranet, allowing people to manage much of their 
lives from home. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Frieden, a telecommunications professor at Penn State  
University, expects to see an increase in fiber optic cable 
installation, particularly in high-income areas and new 
developments. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just like shared-tenant services or intelligent office parks,  
telecommunities are an attempt to carve out a competitive advantage 
in real estate,'' said Robert Frieden, a professor of 
telecommunications at Penn State University. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowry is one of at least seven telecommunities nationwide, with  
dozens more ready to be launched. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the first, Celebration, was built by Disney three years  
ago and is 30 minutes outside of Orlando, Fla. More than 700 homes 
are already connected and students this fall are e-mailing their 
homework to teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Reiman, president of the Broadband Group, a consulting firm,  
said the idea of including advanced home wiring in initial 
architectural plans is winning converts slowly. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't believe phone and cable companies are necessary  
innovative ... so we are pushing the envelope,'' he said. ``One 
reason is because most network providers never anticipate the type 
of appetite for high bandwidth services that our communities 
demonstrate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The amenities come with no additional investment to the  
homeowner, and are provided by U S West -- in the case of Lowry -- 
Cox Communications and AT&AMP;T. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Dresch, director of telecommunications market analysis for  
J.D. Power Associates in Westport, Conn., said from the standpoint 
of telecom companies there are several benefits to getting involved 
early. 
</P>
<P>
	``Customers are prone to purchase multiple services from a  
single provider, mostly out of convenience,'' he said. ``They 
prefer to receive a single bill, and to deal with one company when 
they have problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With technology advancing at such a rapid rate, a house equipped  
with conventional television, phone and electrical wiring is 
obsolete, said Anthony Moiso, president and chief executive officer 
of Rancho Mission Viejo, a 4,000-acre Ladera Ranch community in 
Orange County, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	In-home structured wiring has been added to the design  
guidelines for every home to be built at the development. It will 
enable residents to watch a videotape of satellite program from 
multiple televisions throughout the house and to centralize all 
computers to one printer, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Imagine ... using security sensors to monitor and control home  
lighting or temperature settings via the Internet,'' he said. 
``That's the potential benefit of advanced home wiring.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
