<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Sunday, Oct. 10, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Schroeder's Party Recovers in Berlin Vote  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's Social Democrats  
recovered from a string of losses and held their own in local 
elections Sunday, ensuring that the party would retain a stable 
minority in Berlin's local government. The ballot also marked a 
triumph for incumbent mayor Eberhard Diepgen, who was certain to be 
appointed to a fourth term after a strong vote for the conservative 
Christian Democrats. At a time when Schroeder's austerity plans 
have unsettled Germans, Berliners appeared to opt for the more 
reassuring figure. 

</P>
<P>
	Anger Grows in Flooded Mexican City  
</P>
<P>
	VILLAHERMOSA, Mexico (AP) -- Angry over sandbagging that has  
swamped their neighborhoods and furious that the government hasn't 
done more to help, hundreds of people in Tabasco's flooded capital 
clashed today with police, who beat and arrested many of them. 
President Ernesto Zedillo, who has called the flooding Mexico's 
worst disaster in a decade, toured the stricken areas on Friday and 
yesterday and pledged to send more civilian and military personnel 
to help the victims throughout states along the Gulf of Mexico. 

</P>
<P>
	N. Korea Denounces US Missile Test  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- North Korea denounced the United  
States today for testing a defense missile system over the Pacific, 
and vowed to build up its own defense capabilities. ``This (the 
test) shows that the U.S. policy to stifle North Korea has not in 
the least changed,'' said a commentary in a newspaper for the 
ruling Workers' Party. The U.S. Air Force earlier this month 
launched an unarmed missile and destroyed it with an interceptor 
rocket over the Pacific in its first test of a proposed missile 
defense system. North Korea rattled nerves in Asia last year when 
it test-fired a long-range missile over Japan. 

</P>
<P>
	Chechnya Outlines Peace Plan  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Chechnya's leader outlined a peace plan  
today to end the fighting in his breakaway republic. Chechen 
President Aslan Maskhadov also promised to crack down on renegade 
warlords if Russia withdraws its troops from Chechen territory. 
Maskhadov called on Russia to immediately end ``all combat 
actions,'' and said the two sides should observe the basic 
principles of a 1997 peace accord that ended the 1994-96 Chechen 
war. Maskhadov's plan appears unlikely to make much headway with 
the Russians. 

</P>
<P>
	Delay Sought for Test Ban Vote  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House dispatched Cabinet members  
today to press the Senate to put off voting on a nuclear test ban 
treaty headed for rejection. One Republican opponent, Sen. Jon Kyl 
of Arizona, predicted certain defeat of the Comprehensive Test Ban 
Treaty if a Tuesday vote goes forward. Three Cabinet members and 
the president's top military officer said rejecting the treaty 
would prevent the United States from taking the lead in halting the 
spread of nuclear weapons. 

</P>
<P>
	Thousands Mourn Rail Crash Dead  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Thousands of people sang hymns and prayed in a  
supermarket parking lot in west London today, remembering 40 people 
killed nearby five days earlier when two passenger trains collided. 
Worshippers at churches across the country said special prayers, 
while forensic experts sifted through the charred remains of one 
carriage of the express train that collided with another train 
about two miles west of London's Paddington Station. 

</P>
<P>
	FDA Panel OKs Zoloft for Stress Disorder  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The drug Zoloft, approved in 1992 to treat  
depression, is expected later this year to become the first 
prescription medication specifically approved by the federal 
government for post-traumatic stress. A Food and Drug 
Administration advisory panel on Friday approved the drug's 
expanded labeling, and the agency usually follows its advice. 
However, panelists cautioned the drug so far seems to help only 
women, not men with the anxiety disorder. 

</P>
<P>
	Rams Finally Beat 49ers, 42-20  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The Rams defeated San Francisco 42-20 today,  
breaking a 17-game losing streak against the 49ers and improve to 
4-0. The heroes for the Rams were Kurt Warner, who threw five 
touchdown passes, and Isaac Bruce, who caught four, fitting for a 
team that had been repeatedly beaten by Joe Montana and Steve Young 
throwing to Jerry Rice, a more renowned ``80'' than the oft-injured 
Ram. 

</P>
<P>
	Eagles Defeat Cowboys 13-10  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Eagles beat the Dallas  
Cowboys 13-10 today for their first victory in almost a year. Doug 
Pederson hit Charles Johnson for a 28-yard touchdown as the Eagles 
came back from a 10-point deficit in the fourth quarter. It was 
Philadelphia's first offensive touchdown after 18 quarters without 
one, dating to the first quarter of the season-opening loss against 
Arizona. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KELLY GRUEL  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
