<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Deutsche Telekom in U.S. Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Deutsche Telekom, seeking a major international  
partner, is in talks with Ameritech Corp. and SBC Communications, 
whose merger has just been cleared by U.S. authorities, a newspaper 
reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Welt am Sonntag gave no details on what linkup might be planned.  
Deutsche Telekom spokesman Ullrich Lissek said: ``Right now, 
everybody is negotiating with everybody. But we don't get involved 
in speculation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former German state telephone monopoly has struggled to  
branch out into a global player since being partly privatized in 
recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC and Ameritech are set to become the largest U.S. local phone  
company through a merger worth more than $70 billion, one of the 
largest in U.S. history. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a magazine said Deutsche Telekom wants to dump its  
loss-making Global One partnership with France Telecom and U.S. 
long-distance provider Sprint. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprint will have to leave Global One once its planned $115  
billion merger with MCI WorldCom -- the biggest in corporate history 
-- goes ahead, Focus magazine quoted Telekom chairman Ron Sommer as 
saying. 
</P>
<P>
	And ``if the French offer a good price, they can have Global  
One,'' he said, adding that Telekom had the means for a major 
linkup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Theoretically, we could link up with one of the three big  
telephone companies in the United States -- though that doesn't mean 
we're interested,'' Sommer told Focus. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom chief Bernie Ebbers reportedly said he has major  
plans to take on European telecom operators on their own turf. 
</P>
<P>
	By building up its own network, WorldCom would have excellent  
chances of grabbing business from companies such as Deutsche 
Telekom or Spain's Telefonica, Der Spiegel magazine quoted Ebbers 
as saying. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
