<DOCNO> APW19991010.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 18:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study of Three-Strikes Law Vetoed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO (AP) -- Gov. Gray Davis vetoed a bill on Sunday  
ordering a study of the cost and benefits of California's 
six-year-old three-strikes prison sentencing law, which requires 
terms of 25 years to life for a third felony conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	In his written veto message, Davis praised the three-strikes law  
and said the state Department of Justice, the RAND Corporation and 
others have already studied it and the new study was unlikely to 
produce new information. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis said violent crime has dropped 35 percent since enactment  
of the three strikes law. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
