<HEADLINE> CAW Votes To Accept Daimler Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Canadian Auto Workers union members voted  
overwhelmingly to accept a three-year contract with DaimlerChrysler 
AG, union officials announced Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The contract, which calls for a 3 percent wage increase in each  
year of a three-year package, a $1,000 (Canadian) signing bonus, an 
improved retirement package and other benefits, was approved by 94 
percent of the union members who voted, the CAW said in a news 
release. 
</P>
<P>
	The union had threatened to strike over DaimlerChrysler's  
refusal to force a supplier to recognize the union in the 
supplier's plant. A tentative agreement was reached Tuesday night -- 
about two hours before a strike deadline -- even though the CAW did 
not make any progress on the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The CAW is now negotiating with General Motors of Canada Ltd.  
and has set a strike deadline of midnight, Oct. 19. 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, the United Auto Workers and Ford Motor Co.  
on Saturday announced a tentative agreement on a new four-year 
contract. Workers at General Motors Corp. and Delphi Automotive 
Systems are expected to complete voting on their new contract this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler workers in the U.S. approved their contract last  
month. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
