<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Lawmaker Criticizes Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Disturbed by George W. Bush's criticism of the  
Republican-led Congress, a GOP lawmaker is drawing comparisons with 
another Southern governor who ran against Capitol Hill while 
seeking the presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., cited the example of President Carter,  
a former Georgia governor, in urging Bush to stop attacking 
congressional Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope that he doesn't get in a mode of attacking those of us  
in the majority party who are working very hard to do the people's 
business and then expect to come to the Washington as the president 
and work with us,'' LaHood said Sunday on CBS' ``Face the Nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Jimmy Carter tried that when he was elected president, running  
against the Congress, and couldn't get anything done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the Texas governor and front-runner for the GOP  
presidential nomination, recently criticized the House Republicans' 
plan to alter a tax credit for the working poor in order to help 
balance the budget. ``I don't think they ought to balance their 
budget on the backs of the poor,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	LaHood, who has endorsed Bush and helped raise campaign funds,  
said criticizing GOP lawmakers would not lay the groundwork for 
positive relations between Congress and a Bush White House. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, he wants to win the nomination,'' LaHood said. ``I  
don't fault him for that, but I don't think you do it by knocking 
the majority party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another Republican presidential candidate, Sen. John McCain of  
Arizona, echoed Bush's criticism of the proposal to spread out the 
payment of earned income tax credits to balance the budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason the Republicans went after the working poor is they  
wouldn't go after the special interests,'' McCain said on CBS. 
``They won't take them on because of the big money that controls 
the party.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Sunday that the Senate would not go along with such a  
plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Republican presidential rivals aimed their fire at Bush.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you've got a front-runner in your party that is using the  
language of American liberalism to critique the Congress, that's 
got to be bad news for the election,'' Gary Bauer told CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	``That phrase, 'Don't balance the budget on the backs of the  
poor.' That is a classic Ted Kennedy, Barney Frank, Democratic 
National Committee line that they've been using for 30 years every 
time Republicans try to bring some fiscal responsibility to 
Washington.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bush campaign did not respond immediately to a request for  
comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
