<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Los Padres Fires Almost Controlled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIG SUR, Calif. (AP) -- Firefighters were gaining on two  
wildfires in the Los Padres National Forest that were started by a 
lightning storm a month ago along the central California coast. 
</P>
<P>
	One fire had burned nearly 34,850 acres and was 75 percent  
contained Sunday. The other had burned about 48,815 acres, and 
firefighters expected to have it contained by Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The fires have forced the evacuations of dozens of people,  
including the monks of the New Camaldoli Hermitage monastery, and 
cost an estimated $56 million to fight. Two thousand firefighters 
have been battling the blazes, which started Sept. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Trinity Alps Wilderness in Northern California,  
lightning-sparked fires had consumed 108,363 acres by Sunday, and 
officials said firefighters there continued to make progress toward 
containing them. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
