<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Group Can't Agree on Endorsement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- A grass-roots conservative Republican  
organization on Sunday failed to agree on which GOP presidential 
candidate it would endorse. 
</P>
<P>
	The first National Federation of Republican Assemblies  
convention ended with a vote in which publisher Steve Forbes got 
164 votes, or 62.4 percent, with Pat Buchanan getting 99 votes, or 
37.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But Forbes fell short of the group's by-law requiring a  
two-thirds majority for NFRA endorsement. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-day NFRA convention in Kansas City drew 274 delegates  
from 33 states. On Saturday they held a rally and straw poll that 
featured speeches by GOP hopefuls Forbes, Buchanan, Gary Bauer and 
Alan Keyes. None of the candidates stuck around for Sunday's 
voting. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFRA, started in 1996, is a grassroots organization devoted  
to advancing conservative issues such as school prayer, an end to 
legalized abortion and tax reform. 
</P>
<P>
	Though all GOP candidates were invited, front-runner George W.  
Bush, Elizabeth Dole, John McCain and Orrin Hatch skipped the 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	All eight candidates were on Sunday's first ballot, but a series  
of votes narrowed the field to the two finalists, Forbes and 
Buchanan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
