<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 12:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D'Backs' Season Falls Flat at Finish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- One-hundred victories. The first team to make the  
playoffs in just its second season. The biggest one-year turnaround 
in baseball history. NL West champions. 
</P>
<P>
	All of those accomplishments were little consolation to an  
Arizona Diamondbacks team that felt it was destined for more, a 
team that played some of its worst baseball of the season in its 
first-round loss to the New York Mets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this team was as good as the San Diego team I played  
on that went to the World Series,'' Steve Finley said. ``We had a 
team that could have won the World Series, but we didn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So much went wrong at the end. Randy Johnson couldn't win a  
playoff game, again. Omar Daal's longest season ever showed in a 
tired arm. The bullpen failed. Tony Womack dropped a fly ball that 
could forever haunt him. Finley almost robbed Todd Pratt of what 
proved to be the deciding home run, yet came up empty-handed. 
</P>
<P>
	In the painful aftermath of Saturday's 4-3, 10-inning loss,  
Johnson reminded everyone of what the team had accomplished. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a great regular season. We won 100 games,'' he said.  
``We don't need a complete turnaround. We showed the people of 
Arizona what good major league baseball is all about. We have 
nothing to be ashamed of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson spoke confidently of what lies ahead.  
</P>
<P>
	``With the talent we have on this team, no question we will be  
back,'' he said. ``It's not going out on a limb with the players, 
the leadership, the coaches and the ownership we have, that we will 
be back in the playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet there are many things that must fall neatly into place for  
Arizona to make a return trip to the postseason. Matt Williams, Jay 
Bell, Luis Gonzalez and Finley had among their best, if not the 
best, seasons of their career. A repeat performance from all might 
be too much to ask. 
</P>
<P>
	For the most part, Arizona avoided serious injuries.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson turned 36 on Sept. 10. He had a marvelous season -- 364  
strikeouts and a 2.48 ERA -- but he threw a career-high 271 2-3 
innings. Maybe that had something to do with his shaky performance 
in Game 1 of the playoffs, when he lost his sixth straight 
postseason decision, a major-league record. 
</P>
<P>
	How many more years will he be able to perform at such a high  
level? 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's Todd Stottlemyre, whose strong performance in Game  
2 was one of Arizona's few postseason bright spots. He will be 35 
next May. The final results of his risky experiment of coming back 
without surgery from a 70 percent tear in his rotator cuff are not 
in. He knows the arm could go at any time. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams turns 34 next month. Bell will be 34 in December. The  
window of opportunity for them won't be open for too many more 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	There is the question of Womack's psyche after his Bill  
Buckner-like blunder Saturday that allowed New York to tie the game 
3-3 in the eighth inning. He was not thrilled with being moved from 
second base to right field to begin with, and he had a miserable 
series at the plate (2-for-18). 
</P>
<P>
	Having traded Tony Batista for Dan Plesac, the Diamondbacks  
could use some stability at shortstop. The bullpen is not blessed 
with depth. 
</P>
<P>
	Andy Benes, who lost his spot in the rotation in the postseason  
and didn't throw a pitch against the Mets, has a clause in his 
contract that allows him to become a free agent at the end of this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	At first base, the Diamondbacks must decide whether to stick  
with strong-hitting rookie Erubiel Durazo or give the job back to 
Travis Lee. Lee, who struggled through a bad year at the plate, 
then sprained his ankle, wasn't even with the team in the playoffs. 
He was left off the 25-man roster and went home to Washington 
state. 
</P>
<P>
	Diamondbacks manager Buck Showalter could move Lee to the  
outfield, or the Diamondbacks could trade him, a tough decision for 
a franchise that gave the young player a $10 million signing bonus 
and expected him to be a cornerstone for years to come. 
</P>
<P>
	There seems little question Arizona will be active in the  
offseason. That is the method of operation of owner Jerry 
Colangelo, who spent $118.9 million on free agents and pulled the 
trigger on the trades that brought Womack, Gonzalez and closer Matt 
Mantei to Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks aren't cash-rich. Colangelo had to go back to  
the team's investors for $24 million to meet short-term cash-flow 
needs. But if there is a way, he will try to pull off the deals and 
signings he and those who work for him think the team needs to 
improve. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we weren't disappointed, that would be a problem,''  
Colangelo said. ``As an organization, we have to do the things we 
need to do so we can advance further. We have to grieve a little 
bit, too. We need to get this loss off our chest, roll up our 
sleeves and get ready for spring training.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
