<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Guerrillas Attack Militia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Lebanese guerrillas launched a series of  
attacks on Israeli and allied militia outposts Sunday in southern 
Lebanon, but no casualties were reported, Lebanese security 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The attacks were claimed by the Iranian-backed Hezbollah group,  
the pro-Syrian Shiite Muslim Amal movement and the Lebanese 
Resistance Brigades, a guerrilla faction supported by Hezbollah. 
</P>
<P>
	In separate statements issued in Beirut, the three groups said  
the guerrillas fired rockets and mortar shells at posts manned by 
Israeli forces and militiamen of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon 
Army in an Israeli-occupied border zone in south Lebanon. They 
claimed ``direct'' and ``confirmed hits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lebanese officials in towns near the attacks confirmed them, but  
said there were no casualties. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials, speaking on customary condition of anonymity,  
said Israeli troops and SLA militiamen retaliated by shelling 
suspected guerrilla hideouts near villages facing the occupied 
zone. No casualties were reported from the retaliatory shelling. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli officials did not immediately give a reaction.  
</P>
<P>
	Hezbollah, or the Party of God, is the most active guerrilla  
group fighting to oust 1,500 Israeli soldiers and the 2,500 SLA 
militiamen from the occupied zone. Israel contends that the zone, 
set up in 1985, is necessary to protect its northern towns from 
cross-border guerrilla attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has pledged to withdraw  
Israeli troops from south Lebanon by next July. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
