<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AFL-CIO To Offer Members Web Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Card-carrying union members soon will have  
access to a special Internet gateway designed to connect workers 
with one another, address labor-related issues and serve as a 
high-tech organizing tool, the AFL-CIO said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will be a revolutionary tool for communications,'' said  
Morton Bahr, president of the Communications Workers of America. 
``Can you imagine being able to ask millions of Internet users to 
boycott a product or bombard an elected official with protests?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Web site, which is scheduled to be up and running by Dec. 1,  
is an attempt to create an electronic community for the AFL-CIO's 
68 affiliated unions. The AFL-CIO also was to announce Monday a 
program that will offer affordable computers and Internet access to 
union members. 
</P>
<P>
	The union plans to make Internet access available to union  
members for no more than $14.95 a month, said Ray Abernathy, an 
AFL-CIO spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Union members will be able to finance the purchase of a computer  
for as low as $600, union officials said. The goal is to bring 
families online for less than $30 a month, Abernathy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``With workingfamilies.com, we're helping bridge the growing gap  
between the technological 'haves' and 'have-nots,' and we're also 
giving working families new ways to connect with one another and to 
make their voices heard,'' said John Sweeney, AFL-CIO president. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor officials hope the portal site will become an electronic  
meeting place for the AFL-CIO's 13 million union members and a 
high-tech organizing tool. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
