<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serbs May Withdraw Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANJA LUKA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- The Bosnian Serb Assembly  
on Sunday endorsed a proposal to withdraw a lawsuit against 
Yugoslavia for aggression and genocide in connection with the 
1992-95 ethnic war here. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was filed by the Sarajevo government six years ago in  
the World Court in The Hague. At the time, the government was 
Muslim-dominated. 
</P>
<P>
	After signing of the 1995 Dayton peace accord, the country was  
divided into two entities -- the Bosnian Serbs' ``Republika Srpska'' 
and the Muslim-Croat Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the Bosnian Serbs want to withdraw the suit.  
</P>
<P>
	A session of the Bosnian Serb Assembly was called by the Bosnian  
Serb member of the multiethnic Bosnian presidency, Zivko Radisic. 
</P>
<P>
	The Muslim members of the Assembly said voting on this matter  
was unconstitutional and left the session. Later, a 61-8 vote 
declared the lawsuit was ``destructive for the life and vital 
interests of Republika Srpska and all Serb people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bosnian radio in Sarajevo linked the decision by the Assembly to  
a visit by Radisic and other Bosnian Serbs to Belgrade, where they 
met with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	A statement issued in Belgrade after the meeting said officials  
discussed the implementation of peace and economic and cultural 
cooperation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only those naive citizens really believe they discussed  
culture,'' Bosnian radio said Sunday. Milosevic, it claimed, was 
using the Bosnian Serbs to get rid of the lawsuit against him. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
