<DOCNO> APW19991010.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-10 21:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Machine Tool Spending Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Spending on machine tools in August fell 1.5  
percent from the previous month and was down 11 percent from the 
year-ago August, according to a study by two industry groups 
released Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Companies spent an estimated $435 million for machine tools in  
August, the Association for Manufacturing Technology and the 
American Machine Tool Distributors' Association said in a joint 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	That fell well short of the $442 million for July and the $489  
million spent in August 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Year to date, machine tool consumption is down 35 percent from  
the same period a year ago, totaling $3.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``The year-on-year decline has slowed somewhat as traditional  
markets, such as autos, prop up the market,'' said Don F. Carlson, 
AMT president. ``However, a bottom to this downturn rests with 
calming customers' apprehensions on consumer spending and with a 
building on the fragile recovery in Asia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts consider demand for machine tools a reliable indicator  
of the strength of the manufacturing sector and the overall 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Statistics are compiled from figures submitted by companies  
participating in the U.S. Machine Tool Consumption report. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
