<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Garciaparra Late Addition to Lineup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra apparently made it through  
Sunday night's 23-7 Boston win in good enough condition to play 
again in Monday night's fifth and decisive game in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't suffer any setbacks,'' manager Jimy Williams said  
after the Red Sox evened the best-of-5 division series 2-2. ``I 
think he's OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Williams arrived at Fenway Park before the game, he left  
Garciaparra, who is nursing a bruised right wrist, out of his 
starting lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Garciaparra showed up, tested his wrist and decided he  
could play against Cleveland, after all. So Williams wasted little 
time making room in his lineup for the AL batting champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I know is, he came into my office and said he was ready to  
play,'' Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	So he put Garciaparra at shortstop and removed backup Lou  
Merloni, who was due to bat sixth. Garciaparra took his usual 
cleanup spot, and first baseman Mike Stanley was dropped to sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra went 1-for-3 before Merloni pinch-hit for him in the  
sixth with Boston leading 18-6. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox lost the first two games of the best-of-5 division  
series with Garciaparra. He went 2-for-3 with a homer in Game 1 but 
was 0-for-3 in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox avoided a sweep with a 9-3 win Saturday. Merloni,  
who spent most of the season at Triple-A Pawtucket, went 2-for-3 
with a run and an RBI. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra, hurt when hit by a pitch from Baltimore's Al Reyes  
on Sept. 25, led the AL with a .357 batting average. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indians ``have to think about'' pitching against  
Garciaparra, Boston second baseman Jose Offerman said. ``It's 
something they were talking about (Saturday) when they found out he 
wasn't in the lineup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams didn't put him in originally.  
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want to put a lot of added pressure on this kid,''  
the manager said. ``The trainer taped his wrist and he went out the 
tunnel, and after he got done hitting, he came back and said he 
could play. So I changed the lineup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams wasn't worried that Garciaparra might sustain  
additional damage. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there was any doubt in my mind that I'd be hurting this  
kid,'' Williams said, ``then I wouldn't put him in there in the 
first place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra missed the last five regular-season games after  
playing in the opener of a doubleheader at the Chicago White Sox in 
which Boston clinched the wild-card berth. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston's other injured star, pitcher Pedro Martinez, reported  
improvement after throwing for eight minutes before Sunday's game. 
On Saturday, the Cy Young Award shoo-in stopped throwing after 
about one minute after experiencing discomfort from a strained 
muscle beneath the right shoulder blade he hurt in the opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't hurt the kid,'' said Williams, who plans to start  
Bret Saberhagen in Game 5. ``Just don't think it's wise to start 
him. I don't even know if he can pitch at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to wait,'' Martinez said. ``I just hope the way I  
threw for eight minutes today, I can throw for eight more from the 
mound'' Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
