<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dogs Survive Being Buried by Quake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Lucky the dog lived up to its name.  
</P>
<P>
	Buried for 18 days by Taiwan's earthquake, Lucky and companion  
Paopao, which means ``treasure,'' emerged, wagging their tails, 
from the rubble of their owner's home in devastated Tsaotun town in 
central Taiwan, a newspaper reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The two canines apparently survived the collapse of the bottom  
floor of the house because the large wooden chair they were 
sleeping under blocked falling debris, the China Times said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dogs, rescued Saturday, ate the fish stored in a  
refrigerator smashed open by rubble and drank water from a nearby 
fish tank, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The family of schoolmaster Lin Yen-chen, whose six members all  
survived the quake, had written the pets off as dead. 
</P>
<P>
	But barking was heard as a backhoe was clearing the site,  
causing the family to begin clearing rubble with their bare hands. 
</P>
<P>
	A medical check found both animals dehydrated, but in need only  
of rest and minor medication, the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan's Sept. 21 earthquake, which measured 7.6 in magnitude,  
was its worst in decades, killing more than 2,200 people and 
collapsing thousands of houses. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
